      "writtenOn": "2018-04-25T23:51:00Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "fair enough. but i\u0027d still strongly prefer to have a consistent, known environment to reduce the possibility of weird interactions. what\u0027s the argument in favor of copying over the whole environment?",
      "parentUuid": "c9bda57e_786da507",
      "revId": "4493c8196d28d695a1afbbaf49c01f613a854514",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "cabd2877_65ec2492",
        "filename": "src/chromiumos/cmd/tast/build/build.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 73,
      "author": {
        "id": 1119004
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-04-26T02:10:43Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Argument in favor is that it\u0027s the default/expected unix behavior (exec\u0027ed commands inherit environment from parent).\nAlso in bash, when someone runs:\n$ A\u003d\"some value\" B\u003d\"value2\" foo bar\nThe \"foo\" process gets the specified values for $A/$B, but it also gets all the rest of the environment from the shell. You really have to go out of the way in a shell to clear the environment, e.g. by prepending a command with \"env -i\". It is rarely done in practice.\nGo\u0027s default, if you don\u0027t set cmd.Env, is also to inherit the full environment. It\u0027s only when cmd.Env is non-nil, it clears the environment and only passes the variables in cmd.Env. I think the canonical example in the documentation is written exactly to suggest what the usage should be to get the typical Unix shell behavior.",
      "parentUuid": "ff489b8a_0eb0e882",
      "revId": "4493c8196d28d695a1afbbaf49c01f613a854514",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "7dc19c10_969a92f3",
        "filename": "src/chromiumos/cmd/tast/build/build.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 73,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000042
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-04-26T04:08:21Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "but this isn\u0027t a shell -- i think that the closest analogy would be fork/exec in a C program.\n\ntast wants to build a test bundle in a particular way for the user. the user doesn\u0027t have any knowledge about which other commands tast is going to run; they just asked it to rebuild some tests before running them. controlling the environment within which the compiler runs seems like the best way to make that work in a repeatable way across different systems.",
      "parentUuid": "cabd2877_65ec2492",
      "revId": "4493c8196d28d695a1afbbaf49c01f613a854514",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
